A company might have many parts for making one product. Each part has different tools, workers, and skills. The manager must choose which part fits best for the different jobs of the product. Management might also choose to have other companies do some work. They do this to move fast. Moving fast means giving good quality and being flexible while keeping costs low.

Victorian novels focus on detail and the upper class. Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights are different. They use mystery and strange events. This makes the characters more interesting. It helps us understand their reasons and feelings.

In Oliver Twist, strange things happen like a dream. These reveal Oliver’s deep feelings and what he knows. In one part, Oliver remembers being shot. He feels as if it is a dream. He cannot control what happens. He sees people like Sikes and Crackit in his mind. An unseen hand takes him away. He feels pain but also fear. Oliver cannot control his bad luck. This shows he feels he has no power, even in danger. It seems like Fagin is breaking him. Oliver might be losing hope and cannot react.

In Wuthering Heights, time feels strange. Day and night pass quickly and slowly. The silence is long and the hours are short.

A few years ago, I worked in a program after school. I helped young students with their studies. I was best at English and reading. One teacher asked me to help a boy named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade. Adrian had many problems with reading. It seemed strange to me. Some letters he could say well. Others he could not. Adrian was Latino, but he spoke perfect English. We had a hard time until I met his mother. I was watching a few students while others went on a trip. Then his mother came in. She did not speak English, only Spanish. I spoke a little Spanish, but we could talk. I realized Adrian read fine. He just did not know the English alphabet well. I hope he is doing better now.

I tell this story to talk about language problems in schools, especially in California. It shows the problem is not always clear. Even a child who speaks English well can have trouble reading it. Many agree this problem is real. So, what can we do? For Adrian, the answer was simple. He needed help with reading English, the alphabet, and saying words. But for children who do not speak English well, the answer is not easy. We need to use many ways to help.

The dual language system is a good idea. It is good for all children, not just those who speak Spanish first. Children in two-way programs do better in school. Some fear it costs too much, or not all children will benefit. But that is not true. If we make these programs common, all children will benefit. How do we do this? Do we make all teachers learn two languages? No, that is not easy or fair. But we can have helpers or tutors who speak two languages.

From the time we are children, most of us hear that there is something bigger than us. Some go to Sunday school to learn about it. Others go to Temple or look within for answers. Many accept the religions of their parents. But some do not believe in them at all. They think there is nothing beyond what they know. People may change their beliefs over time. Whatever path we take, we try to understand ourselves through our own view of spirituality. We look for a light to guide us out of darkness.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the front porch of our house. We listened to the rain on the tin roof and smoked our cigarettes. The rain came down hard, drowning the plants by the porch. He looked out at the rain, as if searching or remembering. He had become thinner, and his clothes hung loosely on him. His hair was less than I remembered. He kept looking at the rain, not meeting my eyes. I felt alone and afraid. I could not talk to him about how much I would miss him. Speaking about it would make it too real. I hugged him, sat down, moved my chair closer, and joined him in watching the rain in the June twilight.

My father died in December that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation did not ease his pain, but kept him alive a few more months. I could not see the value in his longer suffering. I wondered what kind of God would allow this. Alone at night, I did not pray. If God was there, He had stopped listening to me long ago.

I did not want to see him die. So I did not. I could not watch the life that created me end. I wanted to remember him as he lived, not as he died. I knew him better than others did. Dad would not want me to watch him die. I stayed in my bed for three days and waited for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor from Caroline was an early supporter of Republicanism. He was mainly a farmer. This work and his short time in politics made him known for his strong views on freedom and government. He believed in a farming system, and this belief shaped his thoughts on government. Taylor thought the United States could create a perfect system because there was no old tradition to stop them. He valued the natural rights of people and said if one right is denied, they all fail. These rights should be safe from government control. Taylor said in a natural state, strong and smart people win, but in a society, this should not happen.

To make an ideal society, Taylor thought the government must consider the good and bad in people. He had firm ideas about right and wrong. He said government actions must be human because people run it. He defined good rules as those that protect private property, help farming, and stop capitalism. He believed a government with good rules would be fair, even if leaders were selfish. He thought self-interest drove people, but it was bad when it hurt society. A good government was needed to control man's bad side and must be watched to avoid bad rules.

Taylor, like other Republicans then, wanted a strict reading of the Constitution. He wanted a small Federal government with only the rights and powers clearly stated in the Constitution. He knew a large Federal government cost a lot and could become controlling. But he also thought a simple reading was risky and could lead to problems without understanding the writers' intent. He saw the Declaration of Independence as the true guide for the United States because it described the country as a group of separate states, not just one nation.

I looked down, not thinking about what I saw. I quietly studied the view in front of me. My mind looked at the picture with no feelings. Thoughts came and went quickly. It felt like I had no real thoughts of my own. I just saw what was there.

Once, an artist I knew told me to buy a book. The book was called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. I wanted to learn to draw since I was six years old. The book teaches about pencils and how the brain sees lines. One idea in the book is to put a square frame around a picture. This makes a complex picture, like fruit in a kitchen, easier to see. You just see the fruit.

But when I looked at the bowl before me, I could not imagine this frame. I was amazed and could only stand and look. Picasso had his blue period, Monet liked green, and Italian artists used many colors. If I thought of myself as an artist, this was the start of my picture, my story, Work in Brown.

I touched my tool for art. My hand moved, and I thought this could be my most creative moment. Water moved smoothly and clearly. Bits of matter broke away and vanished. My hand hit the toilet handle again, trying to flush away the brown mess in the toilet. It stayed stuck.

With a mop in hand, feet apart, and a green tie around my neck, I frowned at the mess left in the toilet. I flushed a few more times, thinking quietly. Then I reached for toilet paper and wrapped my hand like an oven mitt. I stood up straight, bent down, and put my hand into the bowl, like taking a turkey from the oven on Thanksgiving.

Teenagers are dying in car accidents. Many reasons cause this problem for young American drivers. The National Institutes of Health say that part of the problem is that the teen brain is not ready for driving dangers. Teens also do not have much experience driving. This lack of experience leads to more deadly accidents. It also causes more vehicle rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road.

Teens drive worse when they travel with friends. This is something everyone knows. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center did a study about this. It showed a link between the age of passengers and the number of car accidents.

California and other states try to make teen driving safer. They have temporary licenses that limit when teens can drive. These licenses also stop teens from driving with other minors as passengers.

But I think these licenses are not enough. The real problem is that young drivers cannot handle the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman thinks even age 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today says Zuckerman has done research. It shows that people under age 19-20 like to take risks for excitement. It is better to delay driving until this risk-taking goes down. If we keep giving licenses to young teens, deadly accidents will continue. By 2010, many more teens will be ready to drive.

Laws to address this issue could be simple. Schools could still offer driver’s education. But no one under age 18 could drive a car. A provisional permit could be given before a full driver’s license. Teens would still need to complete a certain number of driving practice hours. The number of hours could be like what most states require now. In California, teens need 6 hours of driving with a teacher and 50 hours with an adult. Because the problem is in all states, a national law could protect teens everywhere.

The law I suggest is not a new idea.

This paper talks about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, it gives a short definition of the disorder. Next, it explains how to diagnose CAPD, with common signs. At the end, it talks about how a teacher can help a student with CAPD in a regular classroom.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), is about how well the brain uses information from hearing. It means the brain does not process sounds correctly. People with CAPD can hear normally, so they are not "hearing impaired." But the brain part that helps understand sounds, like words or talking in a noisy place, does not work right.

The disorder called CAPD was first mentioned in the mid-1950s as “auditory imperception” when researchers looked at children with communication problems. In 1954, the Italian team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari started making tests for these children. In 1961, Kimura made dichotic tests to study how the brain understands different sounds. In 1977, a national meeting helped more research on CAPD in children.

CAPD can show in different ways. A person may not know where a sound is coming from. They might find it hard to tell apart different sounds. They may not recognize sound patterns or detect changes in speech, like sarcasm. One sound might block another sound. They may not understand sound clues well or know the order of sounds they hear.

To diagnose CAPD, experts watch how a person listens and performs on hearing tests. These tests can be done by audiologists, speech-language pathologists, psychologists, and others. They use different tools to check hearing-related skills. This includes questionnaires and watching how the person reacts to sounds. There is no single test that always works well for diagnosing CAPD, and the cause is not known. Many tests give the person many sounds at once and ask them to pick out certain ones, like words or numbers. More advanced tests record signals in the ear and measure how the ear responds.

I want to study social work. I plan to work with the Division of Family and Children Services. I want to help children who are hurt or not cared for. I also want to help families with problems. I can bring values to social work. These values are service, respect, being honest, and helping people get along better. I also want to improve in my job. These values are important to social workers and to me.

I have always wanted to help people. But I did not know what job to choose. In high school and college, I saw people run away from their problems. Some used bad ways to cope. I saw this happen, so I chose to study Psychology. I was still unsure about my career. I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009 and took a break. One day, I visited a friend. She introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy. He wanted to leave his abusive parents. The next day, the boy called the police about his parents. I went to his parents' house to see if I could help. I talked to the police about my concerns. I told them I graduated in Psychology. The police asked me to talk to the parents. The parents made excuses. They said their son was causing trouble. After this, I thought about becoming a social worker to help children with family problems.

Social justice is important in social work. Society says the individual is important. We feel sad when we lose someone. But society wants us to be the same as others. I am an individual. I do not want to be like everyone else. In high school and college, I stood against social injustice. I did this in many ways. I colored my hair, wore clothes I liked, pierced my ears, and joined GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance). I fought against racism and discrimination. I believe in social justice and will keep fighting against injustice.

This paper talks about the Biological and Sociocultural models related to insomnia. The biological model looks at genes and medical facts about health. The Sociocultural model examines how environment affects race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review on insomnia explains these models and the studies chosen to help understand them. It also discusses the strong and weak points of these studies.

A sleep disorder can be a primary sleep disorder, related to another mental disorder, or due to other issues. Primary sleep disorders are Dyssomnias or Parasomnias. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder connect to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other sleep disorder categories can come from medical problems or substance use. Dyssomnias include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified. Primary Insomnia means trouble with sleep, and Primary Hypersomnia means trouble staying awake for at least one month. Narcolepsy involves sudden sleep (cataplexy) and automatic REM. Dyssomnias deal with trouble starting and keeping sleep, while Parasomnias are about unusual behaviors during sleep. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep problems related to another mental disorder are due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review mainly talks about insomnia and primary sleep disorders in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders looks at genes, heritable factors, and physical aspects. Neurons in the hypothalamus with orexin help control sleep and being awake. A study with mice found GABAB receptors on these neurons affect sleep. Activating the GABAA receptor helps with sleep. If blocked, it can reduce anxiety and help sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). These results suggest that what happens in mice can apply to humans. It shows genes and environment affect the GABAB receptor in humans. A problem with this receptor could change sleep without medicine. The sociocultural side of this study is if this trait is inherited, it could affect sleep and, in turn, school, work, and daily tasks needing focus.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Many people, including me, find it hard to move around on campus. In my first year, I lived in an East Halls dorm room. This is almost the farthest east part of campus, except for the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from Stuart Hall to classes in places like the Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes, especially when the weather is bad, which happens often in State College. An older alum told me that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by large empty land. Now, that space has sports fields, big new buildings like the Creamery and new health services building, and is surrounded by apartments. As our campus grows, moving from one place to another gets harder. What is the best way to fix this problem? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But just having bikes is not enough. Students need to use them, and the campus must be built to meet bicyclists' needs.

I talked to a friend who started biking again after a few years. He said he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the best way to get around.” Biking is good for your body and is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and some effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many students, I now live off campus, just as far from the center as some dorms. The best choice I made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, which is a 25-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can reduce that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast. The only problem is Pollock Road is the straightest way to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always easy to travel on, with or without a bike. Walking has its good points, but I am too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only good option to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take 30-40 more minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours each week. Adding all the other walking time for classes and appointments would take more time than I have.

Aldous Huxley talks about the danger of technology and capitalism in his book Brave New World. In the story, people care more about the group than the individual. They learn from the start to seek happiness above everything else. The people are like pieces in a big game, following one idea given by the World Controller. If you look at the book with Marxist ideas, you see Huxley is worried about these systems. Words from Marxism like homogeny and reification show that Huxley is talking about problems in the economy of his time.

Capitalism is made fun of through the idea of false consciousness. This means normal people do not understand their real economic status. They only care about their own benefit. This happens because the ruling class controls the workers’ thoughts. In Brave New World, common people like Deltas and Gammas have no real choice. They learn to consume and spend through sleep teaching. The World Controller uses this control. Hegemony means one group rules over others, and this is clear in the story. Lower classes do not see the control. They believe in an idea that helps capitalism. Upper classes know more but do nothing; few like Bernard question their role. The way social classes interact shows the problems of capitalism.

In Brave New World, people do not have real relationships. The characters are not deep, even the main ones. Huxley might be saying that technology and capitalism take away free will and expression. Love and strong emotions do not exist. People talk about women’s looks and women talk openly about their meetings. Each class is happy with their place, showing capitalism’s effect. They follow their role in society, which is like Marxist ideas about workers. They are made to think they are better as long as they keep consuming and obeying.

Almost four years ago, I took a course in Islam at CBC. We often talked about if Islam is a hostile religion. I think this question is very important today. After 9/11, I saw media change from a hostile view of Islam to being more tolerant of Islam in America. In 2001, I do not think we could have had a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, with a Muslim background in his family.

The Biography of the Prophet interests me. I learned in the past that Muhammad forced people to become Muslims. He would conquer tribes and make them follow Islam. But the biography says Muhammad was misunderstood and humble. People then came to see the truth in his teachings.

There are some similarities between Jesus and Muhammad. One is when Muhammad multiplied food for forty men. The writers seem to want Muhammad to be seen as a humble prophet. This writing makes it seem like they are taking ideas from Jesus and giving them to Muhammad.

There are many stories in the biography that show how people became Muslims. But many stories come from third parties. The writer heard from someone who heard from someone else. This makes the stories seem less true to me.

The biography tries to show Muhammad as a godly man who was wise and gentle. But history shows a different side of Muhammad. I wonder if Muslims today know the true history of Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings and beliefs of Jesus were left behind as Christian thought grew after his life. If we look at history, we see Christianity moving away from its start. Today, there is a growing awareness and a trend toward progress. Some traditional people will not change their thinking, but they may not have enough influence. Among Christians, there will be more awareness of history. People will want to know what was added to Christianity after Jesus. It may take a long time, but there will be a change back to the original ideas. A movement will grow to remove added doctrines, like turning back time, until only Jesus' original ideas remain. This trend will spread in the United States and Europe, leading people to follow only Jesus' ideas. Churches will still be strong to guide. As beliefs become more uniform, there will be fewer differences between regions, denominations, and groups. History has many reversions. For example, Christians were once persecuted by the Roman Empire, but later it became a Christian institution. Our country changed from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. A future reversion will happen in the Christian religion, searching for the source and reducing diversity. This will be possible by reading Jesus' words as metaphorical, not literal. 

Looking back in history, we find only Judaism, the start of Christian religion. Monotheism, a divinely revealed religion, and the Hebrew scriptures were core to the religion when Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish people were not united. They were Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and many common people.

I think "The Jungle" shows that people are naturally greedy and self-centered. They care about their own lives and do not care for those below them. "The Jungle" shows this in many ways. The owners and managers of big factories only want to make their companies grow. They do not care about anyone who gets hurt in the process. Upton Sinclair writes about this. He says the buildings stand tall and black against the sky, with smoke rising high. This shows the damage from pollution. The owners do not care about the smoke or the waste from the pens in Packingtown.

The owners and managers do not care about workers who make them rich. They want to save money. Sinclair says the place is full of jealousy and hate. There is no loyalty or decency. A man does not matter against a dollar. Workers must work long hours. They might lose their jobs without notice or help. At that time, there were few laws to protect workers.

This let managers and owners force workers to work faster in bad conditions. The book does not say it directly, but people living and working in Packingtown had to face these terrible conditions. There were no groups to help them. Unions existed, but they often made things worse. Workers were treated badly and could not escape. They were like slaves. They were poor and depended on men as harsh as old slave drivers. Under these conditions, bad behavior was common, like under slavery.

Dream-land is a poem by Edgar Allan Poe. Poe thought it was one of his better poems. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the word "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56. Mabbott says this goes back to Virgil. Virgil talked about an island north of Britain. The Greeks thought this island was the edge of the known world. Virgil did use the word, but there is another source to consider. Poe liked German writers.

This is important because it shows Poe knew Goethe's work. Karl J. Arndt, in his book about Poe and Goethe, notes that their poems are similar. He thinks Poe copied Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature says Goethe was famous for his drama Faust. Faust was published in two parts. The first part came out in 1808. The second part came out in 1832, the year Goethe died. In the second part of Faust, there is a short poem called "The King of Thulé." The poem is about a king. His wife dies after giving him a goblet. After she dies, the king drinks a lot and cries. He remembers his wife. He decides to die and gives his things to his children. But he keeps the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The king in "The King of Thulé" and the king in "Dream-Land" are very similar. They both are about loss and drinking. Faust was made into a romantic drama in 1842 by H. P. Grattan. This was just before Poe used the word Thulé in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe talks about Thulé twice in his works. He mentions "ultima Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum." He also uses it twice in "Dream-Land" as the start and end of the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-Land" can be read together. In "Dream-Land," the speaker talks about Thulé. He says it is dark and lonely. Dead friends haunt him. He sees a world without color. These scenes are like "The King of Thulé" by Goethe. The king has lost his wife and feels lonely. He has no will to rule or live. The poem seems like the speaker is inside Goethe's poem.

Goethe was an important writer. Poe would have known his work. Poe respected Tennyson, and there is a link to Goethe through Tennyson. Poe would have seen Goethe's work in many copies made after the original.

Under California law, if a person is hurt by slipping on applesauce in a store, they might get extra money as punishment for the store. This can happen if the manager knew about the spill and did nothing because he was having dinner. A judge might not dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s claim for extra money easily. To get this money, she must show the manager ignored the danger of the spill and acted badly. Palmer can say Martin should have known not cleaning the spill could harm people because other people were hurt in the store before her accident. Even if Martin’s actions do not seem very bad, it is still reasonable because six people fell in 2009 and he did not keep the store safe.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, a worker named Rich Wayne told his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill. Martin said he was on a dinner break and could not handle it. At 5:15 pm, another worker, Mary J. Haddigan, also told Martin, but he said the same thing. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped on the spill and hurt her back badly. Before Palmer’s fall, five other people had fallen in the store in 2009. Palmer is suing the store for money for her injury and for punishment. We are thinking about trying to stop her claim for punishment money.

In California, a person can get punishment money if the other person acted with “oppression, fraud, or malice.” Malice means trying to cause harm or acting very badly without caring for others’ safety. Courts say actions are malicious when the person knew their actions could be dangerous and still did nothing to stop it.

She always felt like she needed something. It was a desire that could not be filled. This started when she was 14, just becoming a teenager. It was still there when she was 17. By then, she knew she wanted someone, not something. But she was not interested in any boys. Some boys liked her and tried to win her over, but no one caught her interest. She often asked herself why this happened. She thought about what could make a teenage girl feel this way. Over the years, she had ideas, but none seemed right. So she lived her life, always wondering about her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were calm and good people. They did not argue with each other, and they rarely argued with her. The only thing they argued about was her need for independence and freedom. She was the daughter of a calm couple, but she had a fun and lively personality. This made her very likable, and she was a nice person.

Today, though, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, looking for new ideas, she heard a short scream from the kitchen. It was her mother's voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic. "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" she asked. She saw her mother on the ground, in pain, saying "Ow" with short breaths. The daughter went to her and tried to help. "Ouch ... swee - ty, I ... need you to take me to - the hospital," her mother said in a rushed voice. The daughter knew her mother was in great pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up," she said. Her mother pointed, and the daughter was glad she had learned how to be strong. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back, and drove.

The hospital had the smell of cleaning and sickness, mixed with fear. But she did not notice, as she was busy helping her mother. She quickly carried the injured woman inside and called for help. Some worried faces gathered, and someone brought a rolling bed for her mother. They took her mother away to be looked at, while the daughter sat and worried.

Her mother had fallen off a stool while trying to get a vase from the top cabinet.

This study shows that following a Mediterranean Diet (Med diet), with a high alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score, is linked to lower risk of long-term heart disease and stroke. The aMed diet is a changed form of the Med diet. It includes more plant foods like fruits, nuts, whole grains, and beans. It also includes plant proteins and uses monounsaturated fat instead of saturated fat. Fish is part of the diet, with less animal products and saturated fats. Alcohol in small amounts is allowed.

Earlier studies showed that following a Med diet is linked to lower risk of death from all causes and heart problems. One study found the Med diet better than a low-fat diet for weight loss and lowering bad cholesterol in overweight people. Past studies did not focus on stroke.

This study looked at 74,886 women aged 38 to 63. These women had no history of heart disease or diabetes. They were part of the Nurses' Health Study, which includes 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors looked at aMed diet scores using food reports given by the nurses. Reports were checked for accuracy. Health records or death certificates confirmed heart disease and stroke cases. If records were missing, cases were called "probable" and included. About 17% of strokes and 24% of nonfatal heart attacks were in this group. Body weight, smoking habits, aspirin use, vitamin use, menopause status, and hormone use were noted. From 1986, physical exercise was also noted.

To show long-term eating patterns, average aMed scores from reports over two years were used. Changes were made for factors like age, smoking, body weight, menopause status, hormone use, vitamin use, alcohol use, exercise, and aspirin use.

Researchers used a model to study the link between aMed scores and risk of heart disease and stroke. They looked at fatal and nonfatal heart disease and stroke separately.

Women who followed the Mediterranean diet more closely had a lower risk of heart disease and stroke. In 20 years, there were 2391 new heart disease cases, 1763 stroke cases, and 1077 deaths from heart disease and stroke. Women with the highest aMed scores had a lower risk of heart disease and stroke than those with the lowest scores. Their risk was 0.71 times that of women in the lowest group.

The sign says Hitler is alive in Burma.

Ellen Page, star of the movie Juno, stands alone on a street corner. She holds a piece of cardboard above her head. The message is written with a marker on her sign. Burma, also called Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia. It is ruled by a strict military group. This group took power in 1962 through a coup. In 2007, people protested in the streets for the first time in ten years. Many Burmese monks led these protests. The protests were called “The Saffron Revolution” because of the color of the monks' robes. At first, the government let the monks protest peacefully. But soon, violence broke out. The military attacked and damaged monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were arrested. A Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007, during a protest. The government said 13 people were killed. But Colonel Hla Win, who left the army before the report, said many more people died. He said the bodies could be in the thousands.

This is not new. Governments have always tried to stop protests and keep control. Long ago, Roman emperors said they were chosen by gods to rule everything. Japanese emperors were thought to be gods. They were meant to lead their people to success. Our president, George W. Bush, talks weekly with Ted Haggard, who leads a group called Stupid People Worldwide, which is part of the Republic Party.

Some famous examples of these actions include the protest at Tiananmen Square on June 4, 1989. Students, workers, and thinkers protested against the government. The number of dead people differs. The Chinese government said 200-300 people died. But the Chinese Red Cross said 2,000-3,000 people died. Another example is the Rwandan genocide in the 1990s. Hutu groups, helped by the Rwandan government, killed Tutsis and political moderates. Hitler’s ‘Third Reich’ is another example. During this time, people of Jewish background were killed across several countries.

Duke Ellington is famous in jazz for his long career and his skill in leading his band. He played piano quietly in many songs, but he was a great composer. Ellington wrote music that showed off the talents of his band members. He made music where soloists could play freely and wrote parts that fit the style of each musician. This made the whole band sound unique and original. Ellington knew how each player sounded and how they fit together, which helped him create some of the best jazz music ever.

The Grove Music dictionary talks about Ellington's sound and new ideas. It mentions Creole Love Call, where he used the voice as a jazz instrument. This song shows Ellington's skill in adding sound and color without words. It also shows how he worked with soloists. Creole Love Call is a slow blues song with six parts:

Chorus 1: A call and response between voice and reeds. The voice starts smooth and ends rough.
Chorus 2: A muted trumpet plays the melody with special blue notes.
Chorus 3: A high clarinet solo with a soft piano in the background.
Chorus 4: The full band echoes the first chorus with brass and reeds.
Chorus 5: The reeds start the call and response in a high pitch, with the brass and rhythm sections adding stops.
Chorus 6: Like the first chorus, with the voice using a "growl" sound as an instrument.
Tag: A short vocal run and a strange ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add sound color is a key part of his work.

In Hot and Bothered, Ellington mixes tight band writing with sound color. "Bubber" Miley on trumpet and Baby Cox with scat singing create a rich sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) shows these ideas too. Here, Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton plays the melody on trombone in a great way.

Why do living things change over time the way they do? Are there limits that affect how they change? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said, "Even now the zoologist has scarce begun to dream of defining in mathematical language even the simplest organic forms." This is still true today. Recently, people have used math models to study how mollusks make their shells over time. Our study looks at how math models and experiments can help us understand changes in Prunum. We used X-ray pictures of Prunum to find numbers we could use to make models of their shells. These numbers went into a computer program called CerioShell. We made models of shells to see how much they can change. We combine these models with other studies to understand big changes in this group of animals.

A shell is like a tube that turns around over time. These turns are called whorls. They go around a line called the columella in the middle of the shell. Whorls can get bigger at different speeds. A line called a suture separates each whorl. The biggest whorl is usually the last one, called the body whorl. The spire is all whorls except the last one. The top of the spire is the apex, and the bottom is the base. The animal comes out of the shell through an opening called the aperture.

You can look at shells from different sides: the top, bottom, front, and back. Usually, people look at shells from the front, with the opening facing them and the top pointing up.

To count whorls, first look at the shell from the top. Find where the first line begins. Draw a line to divide the shell into two parts. Count the whorls from this line, estimating to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell is a series of openings that move through time and space as the animal builds it. You can track the path of these openings using points for the center of each whorl's opening, and the size of the opening from side to side and top to bottom.

You can show this path on a graph and with math. Once you have a math formula, you can change how the mollusk makes its shell.

The number of newborn and infant deaths in Indonesia has not changed much in the last ten years. Indonesia is making progress on some goals like clean water and sanitation. But, child and mother health is not improving fast enough to meet the goals by 2015. The reasons for this will be explained below. The country needs to make the health system stronger instead of just focusing on specific programs.

Indonesia has improved the number of births with a skilled health worker. Now, 72% of births have a skilled worker. But this includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot help if there are problems in the pregnancy. This is why many mothers die from bleeding. So, even though the numbers look better, more work is needed. Also, fewer children under five are getting treated by a health worker when they have diarrhea. The data on care after birth is not complete, but this is also a concern. The rates are low across the country.

Cesarean-section rates are about 4%, which is low. In cities, the rate is 7%, but in rural areas, it is only 2%. This shows that healthcare is more available in cities. There is also a big gap between rich and poor. The poor have a harder time getting healthcare because of high costs.

To improve care for mothers and newborns, we need to decide how to fix the lack of services. Should Indonesia focus on specific programs, or make the whole health system better? Focusing on specific programs is attractive because it is easier to manage and gives quick results. But there are problems. Putting too much money into one area can take resources away from others. For example, more money for HIV/AIDS affects family planning. Also, running many separate programs can lead to extra paperwork and problems with organization.

Popular Music has many types. Over the past 100 years, it has grown to include many different kinds. It is hard to list them all. Each type, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, has smaller types within it. Heavy Metal rock is one type. It has become very diverse and expressive in the past 40 years. It shows many emotions, though often they are dark. It is diverse because it can change a lot. People saw this early on and made their own new types. This led to even more smaller types, and it keeps growing.

Today, heavy metal has many small groups. It is hard to say what heavy metal is exactly. It includes many ideas from other types of music. But, it started somewhere. To understand metal music today, we must know what the metal movement is and why it is more than just a type of music.

Metal is a movement with a lot of darkness. It is "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more show. Less simple, more skill. People in metal bands are very good at playing music. Metal is also linked to drugs. In the mid-70s, many people used drugs, which led to wild, strange music. These drugs were often blamed for this music. Metal has many dark, strong qualities. This was new because much popular music was not this dark. Later metal got ideas from dark things in the Romantic Era. Lyrics from that time show this darkness. 

The song "Helter Skelter" shows the dark side of the Beatles. It is up and down, like drugs. Some say it was one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a reply to a Rolling Stones song that was also dark. The Beatles wanted to show they could be as heavy as the Stones, so they put this song on The White Album.

Before Surrealist artists made dreamlike art, Henri Rousseau was making his own dream art. He did this both in real life and in his mind. In 1910, Rousseau painted The Dream. This painting shows a woman amazed by the dream world she visits. It also shows Rousseau's own dreams and hopes as an artist. Since he started painting, Rousseau wanted other artists and art lovers to notice and praise him. But he faced a hard choice. He had to decide if he should follow common art styles to be accepted or be different and create his own style.  

To understand The Dream, it helps to know about Rousseau's life. Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware seller. Rousseau did not learn art in school. Instead, he worked for the French toll service until he was forty. People wrongly called him a customs inspector. After his first wife, Clémence, died, along with eight of their children, Rousseau was left with one child, Julia, and much sadness. He wanted a new life and started painting to feel better. Unlike other artists of his time, Rousseau was a folk painter who had the dreams of a common man.  

Rousseau wanted to be accepted by the art world. This makes sense because he did not have formal art training and started late. He painted at the same time as many famous artists. Though he worked for many years, people only noticed his art when Matisse became well-known. In the book Modern French Painters, Jan Gordon says that even though Matisse and Rousseau both painted, they were different. Matisse feared painting in a boring way. Rousseau wanted to paint in a traditional way to be accepted by the art world.

Many great thinkers have suggested there is a connection between ethics and beauty, between truth and beauty. I think there is a good reason for this. As John Keats writes in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” We learn much in life through education or experience. Yet, we seem to understand ethics and beauty, as Keats says, without being taught in the usual ways. Ethics and beauty try to describe rather than give rules. We try to explain why art or literature is beautiful or why an action is moral, instead of making rules for good art or moral behavior.

When we talk about art or morals, we cannot fully explain what is good or beautiful. A talk about da Vinci's Mona Lisa might focus on foreground, background, contrast, or culture, but these do not explain why it is good art. Often, when asked about a favorite work of art or literature, people say, “There's just something about it” before giving a deeper explanation. I think art and morals cannot be fully described by their qualities. Flannery O'Connor said, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how well we describe a work of literature, something beyond the words remains. I think ethics has this same quality. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental.” This “something”, this special quality, is the strongest part of art and morality. This special quality connects ethics and beauty.

I believe morality and art are closely related because we feel both deeply, even if we cannot explain them fully. This link is stronger in literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there.”

Today, Germany is a strong, united country. It has its own culture from München in the Alps to Kiel by the Baltic Sea. This culture is also in Köln on the Rhine River and in Dresden on the Elbe River. Germany's culture is unique and comes from many sources and tribes.

Germania is where the Germans come from. The name's origin is debated by experts. Tacitus said it came from a tribe called Tungrians, who were once called Germans. They crossed the Rhine and fought the Gauls. Julius Caesar first used "Germanus" in his writings about the Gallic Wars. He got this word from the Gauls to tell apart the Gauls he conquered from the tribes he did not. Some think it means a neighbor in the Gaulish language. Others think it comes from the spear called "ger" or from the Old Irish word "garim" meaning "to shout."

Tacitus, a Roman historian, wrote in AD 98 about the Germans' origins. He said Germans were original and not mixed with other races. He wondered why anyone would leave Asia or Africa for Germany, with its wild lands and bad weather, unless it was home.

Romans did not want to move to Germania. They explored it for goods and sometimes led campaigns there, but they mostly returned to Rome. By the middle of the first century, Germanic tribes lived by the Roman Empire's borders. They traded goods and served in the Roman army.

The play Twelfth Night shows that using a disguise can help someone trick others for a long time. But in the end, a person must stop pretending. If not, they might lose who they really are. The problem with ending a trick is that it can make people feel alone. So, a person must choose between being true to themselves or keeping their relationships with others. Some people may not mind being tricked, but others will be upset and feel hurt by it.

The issue of pretending to be a different gender is especially difficult. It makes us ask why someone would hide their true identity. In Viola's case, she dresses as a man to protect herself: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249). 

Viola is in a new land and thinks she must look like a man to be safe. Her plan works, but it also makes her feel separate from the women around her. This cuts her off from friends. Things become more complicated when Olivia falls in love with her because Olivia thinks she is a man: “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138). Viola also has hidden feelings for Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261).

To a modern reader, Twelfth Night might show how pretending can reveal hidden feelings. This happens with Olivia and Orsino. Some parts of the play hint that they might have unspoken desires that Viola's disguise makes them face. For example, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because she thinks Cesario is a man, or does she have feelings for women? It seems likely that Olivia is making fun of people who only care about looks. This is clear when Olivia easily switches her love from Cesario to Sebastian and sees Cesario/Viola as family: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315).

German rule in Africa was often harsh. This was clear in German South West Africa, now Namibia. There, the Germans killed many Ovaherero and Nama people. But not all German colonies were the same. They had different rules and ways of leading. Education was also different in each colony. When the British took control of German East Africa in 1919, they found many educated Africans. German schools in Kamerun and other places were also well regarded. South West Africa was different. There, the government did not set up many schools for local people. Instead, missionary groups ran most schools with little help from the government. The government spent more on schools for Europeans. These choices affected South West Africa for a long time. Most local people did not get an education and could not read or write. Many reasons led to these differences. This paper will explore these reasons and look at new studies on how settlers and leaders treated local Africans.

There are many writings about education in German colonies. Most are in German and were written in the early 1900s. They mostly describe schools in the colonies. Later, English writings compared education in different German colonies. These studies showed big differences in colonial schools. Cohen wrote about schools in South West Africa and East Africa. He compared them and explained why they were different. He said many settlers in South West Africa affected its schools.

South West Africa had a warm climate, unlike some other German colonies. Much of it was desert. Because of this climate, many Europeans lived there. By 1913, almost 15,000 Europeans lived in South West Africa. In East Africa, another colony, there were only 5,336 Europeans.

The United States and Mexico are examples of two countries that had a long rivalry. This rivalry lasted 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The main event in this rivalry was the Mexican-American War from 1846 to 1848. During this war, the United States attacked and won against Mexico, taking Texas and the American Southwest. There were many other conflicts between these two countries until just before World War I. The rivalry started because Americans and Mexicans disagreed on religion, culture, and other important matters.

This situation is similar to many countries that have rivalries with their neighbors. Countries that share a border often have conflicts. These conflicts can lead to rivalries. The United States and Mexico are not the only countries with a long rivalry with a neighbor. David M. Pletcher says that Mexico and Cuba are the only countries with long-lasting diplomatic problems with the United States. Both are close to the United States and have been rivals, while other Latin American countries have had good relations with the United States.

Religious issues caused a problem between the United States and Mexico, as they have in many places throughout history. Sally Frahm says that in the 1800s, Americans were against Catholicism and monarchy, much like they were against fascism and communism in the 1900s. The rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union during the Cold War was both about ideas and important interests. But in the case of the United States and Mexico, the struggle was about religion, not politics. This distrust came from past tensions between English and Spanish people. These feelings made it hard for the United States and Mexico to have good relations.

Diehl and Goerts list 17 disputes between the United States and Mexico during their 57-year rivalry. Most of these disputes were about border issues and raids from Mexico. There were also problems with bandits and outlaws in American border towns. These issues continued until both countries used military force at their borders.

According to Schmitt, the rivalry started to end when Mexico became dependent on the United States. It finally ended when American goals changed from taking land to having economic influence in Mexico in the late 1800s.

Fifteen years ago, I became sick and disabled by an illness I did not know about before.

I was a nurse then. I chose this job because I needed safety and security. I did not have these when I was a child. People said, "You will always find work; people will always get sick." I heard this many times as I grew older. So, even though I wanted to be a scientist or a journalist, I chose nursing.

But then I was 46 years old, single, with no money and unable to work. Today, I am still disabled. After 15 years on Social Security Disability, I have nothing left to call "mine." I get by, but each day is hard. It hurts my sense of safety and self-worth. Nothing is certain. But I know one thing is true: I could not have managed without my family and a few good friends. Even if I was strong, real problems can make you feel weak.

Emergencies happen in life, both big and small. We cannot always be prepared. Some things are too big to handle alone.

In the U.S., we need to stop relying only on big government. It is not strong and is falling apart. Instead, I hope Americans learn to trust and help each other. It is better than each person building a shelter alone.

Some talk about "rugged individualism" in the U.S. But what helped people in the past was kindness, respect, and sharing. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies did not make it alone.

So, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit: first aid supplies, water tablets, plastic for windows, flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, and canned food. If you have land for a small farm and can preserve food, do it. It is a good idea, and so is a wood stove if you do not live in an apartment.

But also, get to know your neighbors.

A long time ago, in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born. He would later be known as Buddha. During his life, he gave up the world and became wise. His teachings started a religion called Buddhism. The oldest group of this religion is Theravada Buddhism. This religion is about 2,500 years old. It is different today than when Buddha was alive. For example, in Sri Lanka, a Theravada country, people have a yearly water-cutting ceremony. Monks and regular people take part in this event. It is important to them, even though Buddha never talked about such a celebration. These changes can be seen in both small traditions and big ideas of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist group, both monks and regular people, had to change their beliefs over time. This is because of different forces, both from inside and outside, and both friendly and unfriendly.

There are some important ideas in this discussion. One idea is internal versus external. An internal force comes from members of the Buddhist community, whether they are monks or not. An external force comes from people who are not Buddhists. A hostile force tries to harm the Buddhist community. A benign force does not try to help or hurt the community, but it might do one or the other by chance. These ideas will be used a lot in this discussion.

First, we need to look at the main ideas of the religion. Buddhists find safety in three things: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is made up of three parts of Buddhist text, called the Tripitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has all the Suttas. The Vinaya Pitaka has the rules for behavior. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has the deep ideas of Buddhism. These ideas include Anatta, which means no soul; Dukkha, which means life is full of suffering; and Anicca, which means everything changes. By understanding these ideas, one can end the cycle of death and rebirth, called Sansara. With Sansara, desire, hatred, and wrong beliefs will also end when someone becomes wise. The Vinaya Pitaka gives rules for life. Regular people have five rules: do not kill, do not lie, do not steal, do not misbehave sexually, and do not use drugs. Monks have many more rules to follow. The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. First, life is suffering. Second, being attached causes suffering. Third, suffering can be stopped.
